00:00:18.120 --> 00:00:23.120
[Amit Varma]: I grew up in the 1980s and 1990s when the state of the media looked very different from today

00:00:23.600 --> 00:00:28.200
[Amit Varma]: Everyone got the news from a handful of mainstream newspapers and magazines and TV stations

00:00:28.200 --> 00:00:33.760
[Amit Varma]: And while there may have been some biases here and there, there was by and large a consensus on the truth

00:00:33.760 --> 00:00:36.200
[Amit Varma]: All of us lived in the same world

00:00:36.600 --> 00:00:39.760
[Amit Varma]: But that world has changed. The media is fragmented

00:00:39.760 --> 00:00:44.880
[Amit Varma]: We all get our news and facts from different sources and there is no longer that consensus

00:00:44.880 --> 00:00:46.440
[Amit Varma]: We can all choose the reality

00:00:46.440 --> 00:00:53.560
[Amit Varma]: We wish to inhabit and can find supporting facts from it whether those facts are true facts or alternative facts as the lingo now goes

00:00:53.560 --> 00:01:00.620
[Amit Varma]: We can all choose to form our own echo chambers and we can all choose to live in different worlds. In all of this

00:01:00.700 --> 00:01:04.380
[Amit Varma]: What does it mean to be a journalist? Are we all just suppliers?

00:01:04.980 --> 00:01:10.140
[Amit Varma]: Fulfilling the demands of a particular segment of the marketplace or do we have a dharma that goes beyond that?

