00:02:59.460 --> 00:03:03.460
[Amit Varma]: Welcome back to the scene in the unseen Siddharth and Peter welcome to the show

00:03:03.460 --> 00:03:04.460
[Guest 1]: Hi Amit lovely to be here

00:03:04.460 --> 00:03:08.460
[Guest 1]: Thank you Amit it's been a while coming but I'm happy I'm here

00:03:08.460 --> 00:03:14.460
[Amit Varma]: Siddharth you were mentioning earlier when we were chatting before the show that you started working in 1976

00:03:14.460 --> 00:03:15.460
[Amit Varma]: That's right

00:03:15.460 --> 00:03:16.460
[Amit Varma]: What brought you into journalism?

00:03:16.460 --> 00:03:25.460
[Guest 1]: So one story that I give out is that jobs employment in those days was difficult for a generalist graduate

00:03:25.460 --> 00:03:34.460
[Guest 1]: The services were obviously one option and I was not good enough for it and nor was I interested quite honestly

00:03:34.460 --> 00:03:41.460
[Guest 1]: The State Bank of India probationary exam was the other and banking did not excite me

00:03:41.460 --> 00:03:48.460
[Guest 1]: So really by and large the chances of getting a proper job employment was difficult

00:03:48.460 --> 00:03:52.460
[Guest 1]: The economy was growing a bit slowly and there was the emergency

00:03:52.460 --> 00:04:03.460
[Guest 1]: So things were ironically joining you know as a journalist during the emergency was a look like a very counterintuitive decision

00:04:03.460 --> 00:04:09.460
[Guest 1]: But I got to know that there were some jobs going for trainees in the free press journal

00:04:09.460 --> 00:04:16.460
[Guest 1]: Which was in those days a very very feisty small independent minded newspaper

00:04:16.460 --> 00:04:24.460
[Guest 1]: And I applied there was a test of general knowledge writing skills etc

00:04:24.460 --> 00:04:30.460
[Guest 1]: Some 30-40 people applied they took three abysmal salary

00:04:30.460 --> 00:04:36.460
[Guest 1]: But I had a kind of fondness for writing I had actually written for them as a freelancer

00:04:36.460 --> 00:04:42.460
[Guest 1]: So got it and that's how I began and as I said it was the emergency

00:04:42.460 --> 00:04:47.460
[Guest 1]: In fact it was bang in the middle of that 19 month period

00:04:47.460 --> 00:04:54.460
[Guest 1]: Difficult times to be quite honest even me at even I at my level felt those things

00:04:54.460 --> 00:04:58.460
[Guest 1]: You couldn't write so many things copy had to be sent to censors

00:04:58.460 --> 00:05:05.460
[Guest 1]: But as I now like to say you eventually get through the darkest periods

00:05:05.460 --> 00:05:10.460
[Amit Varma]: And so because those were the days of the emergency and you know you said you picked free press journal

00:05:10.460 --> 00:05:15.460
[Amit Varma]: In particular because of a feisty were you then also driven at the time by a sense of purpose

00:05:15.460 --> 00:05:17.460
[Amit Varma]: Like what was journalism to you what was your duty

00:05:17.460 --> 00:05:22.460
[Guest 1]: I don't think I at least and there were hardly any training institutes

00:05:22.460 --> 00:05:31.460
[Guest 1]: I don't think there were I don't think that kind of mission sense of mission was driving any journalist

00:05:31.460 --> 00:05:35.460
[Guest 1]: But you always understood a few things instinctively

00:05:35.460 --> 00:05:42.460
[Guest 1]: First of all the emergency had made even largely a political types into political animals

00:05:42.460 --> 00:05:46.460
[Guest 1]: It didn't show up in the media but we were kind of there

00:05:46.460 --> 00:05:52.460
[Guest 1]: And as a student in a college which had all these lefties hanging around

00:05:52.460 --> 00:05:56.460
[Guest 1]: You know even Bombay was pretty fired up in those days

00:05:56.460 --> 00:06:03.460
[Guest 1]: I there was a sense and somehow writers and those kind of people came into one's orbit

00:06:03.460 --> 00:06:08.460
[Guest 1]: And you got to know about journalism so that sense was there

00:06:08.460 --> 00:06:17.460
[Guest 1]: The sense of mission unstated unwritten non codified was there in the newsroom

00:06:17.460 --> 00:06:22.460
[Guest 1]: And it permeated your DNA very very rapidly in many ways

00:06:22.460 --> 00:06:28.460
[Guest 1]: For example you sense that you had to write the underdogs point of view

00:06:28.460 --> 00:06:35.460
[Guest 1]: The citizens voice made it to the pages of the newspapers including the bigger ones

00:06:35.460 --> 00:06:40.460
[Guest 1]: Rather than you know business did not dominate the economy the way it does now

00:06:40.460 --> 00:06:44.460
[Guest 1]: So if you wrote something about big business no harm done

00:06:44.460 --> 00:06:48.460
[Guest 1]: Business sections were small there were hardly any papers

00:06:48.460 --> 00:06:54.460
[Guest 1]: You covered trade unions again I wish to make this a special point

00:06:54.460 --> 00:06:58.460
[Guest 1]: The city this city was a working-class city at that time

00:06:58.460 --> 00:07:01.460
[Guest 1]: Strong trade unions mill workers unions

00:07:01.460 --> 00:07:05.460
[Guest 1]: So you covered them you went to their press conference

00:07:05.460 --> 00:07:08.460
[Guest 1]: That railway strike had just happened in 74 so it was

00:07:08.460 --> 00:07:15.460
[Guest 1]: So it came in that not that you were a activist

00:07:15.460 --> 00:07:18.460
[Guest 1]: None of us were allowed to be activists

00:07:18.460 --> 00:07:24.460
[Guest 1]: But you realize that you needed to get common voices into the pages of paper

00:07:24.460 --> 00:07:29.460
[Guest 1]: So I suppose if you want to term it as a mission that gets in

00:07:29.460 --> 00:07:32.460
[Guest 1]: The mission of course you mentioned the truth

00:07:32.460 --> 00:07:35.460
[Guest 1]: I don't think that was our mission our mission was to get the facts right

00:07:35.460 --> 00:07:39.460
[Guest 1]: Right I always say leave the truth to those guys in the Himalayas

00:07:39.460 --> 00:07:44.460
[Guest 1]: Get your facts right and I think we have started playing fast and loose with facts

00:07:44.460 --> 00:07:46.460
[Guest 1]: Siddharth when did you see this changing

00:07:46.460 --> 00:07:50.460
[Guest 1]: In two or three different ways the changes have been coming

00:07:50.460 --> 00:07:54.460
[Guest 1]: One of the big changes was this will sound very unconnected in the beginning

00:07:54.460 --> 00:08:02.460
[Guest 1]: But when salary started going up in the 80s

00:08:02.460 --> 00:08:05.460
[Guest 1]: Journalists a better class of educated journalists came in

00:08:05.460 --> 00:08:12.460
[Guest 1]: Magazines sprung up and businessmen started investing

00:08:12.460 --> 00:08:15.460
[Guest 1]: A magazine which were glossy came up

00:08:15.460 --> 00:08:19.460
[Guest 1]: So there was a demand for journalists from publications

00:08:19.460 --> 00:08:22.460
[Guest 1]: There was a lot of movement around and when salary started going up

00:08:22.460 --> 00:08:27.460
[Guest 1]: Two things happened one is that the old wage board system stopped

00:08:27.460 --> 00:08:29.460
[Guest 1]: And the contract system came in

00:08:29.460 --> 00:08:33.460
[Guest 1]: And the contract system allowed you to get really handsome salaries

00:08:33.460 --> 00:08:38.460
[Guest 1]: No longer controlled by a central agency

00:08:38.460 --> 00:08:41.460
[Guest 1]: The second thing that happened is that

00:08:41.460 --> 00:08:44.460
[Guest 1]: Journalists started becoming part of the establishment

00:08:44.460 --> 00:08:47.460
[Guest 1]: Because now they were getting paid better

00:08:47.460 --> 00:08:49.460
[Guest 1]: They were wearing better clothes

00:08:49.460 --> 00:08:52.460
[Guest 1]: They were moving around in circles business journalism had come in

00:08:52.460 --> 00:08:57.460
[Guest 1]: So journalists started thinking that they were on equal terms with big business etc

00:08:57.460 --> 00:09:01.460
[Guest 1]: When that happens you come close to those people you are writing about

00:09:01.460 --> 00:09:07.460
[Guest 1]: And really honestly journalists shouldn't have two close friends

00:09:07.460 --> 00:09:12.460
[Guest 1]: From anyone in the establishment political economic anything

00:09:12.460 --> 00:09:16.460
[Guest 1]: I'm sure you read the film press or the sports media and all that

00:09:16.460 --> 00:09:21.460
[Guest 1]: You'll rarely see critical articles because they're so close in a sense embedded

00:09:21.460 --> 00:09:24.460
[Guest 1]: The same thing with politics and the same thing with business

00:09:24.460 --> 00:09:28.460
[Guest 1]: So that was one shift

00:09:28.460 --> 00:09:33.460
[Guest 1]: The other shift came when in the 90s

00:09:33.460 --> 00:09:38.460
[Guest 1]: This new concept came of invitation price

00:09:38.460 --> 00:09:41.460
[Guest 1]: I'm sorry I'm taking up too much time

00:09:41.460 --> 00:09:44.460
[Guest 1]: But the invitation price of a publication

00:09:44.460 --> 00:09:47.460
[Guest 1]: I got my morning paper for two rupees

00:09:47.460 --> 00:09:50.460
[Guest 1]: One rupee actually when it began

00:09:50.460 --> 00:09:52.460
[Guest 1]: This was a Murdoch formula

00:09:52.460 --> 00:09:56.460
[Guest 1]: If I'm getting it at one rupee and the cost of production is nine rupees

00:09:56.460 --> 00:09:58.460
[Guest 1]: Who subsidizes the rest?

00:09:58.460 --> 00:10:00.460
[Amit Varma]: The advertiser

00:10:00.460 --> 00:10:06.460
[Guest 1]: The advertiser subsidize 80, 85, 90 percent of your price

00:10:06.460 --> 00:10:12.460
[Guest 1]: Goes to show that the advertiser has control over 80 to 90 percent of your revenue

00:10:12.460 --> 00:10:14.460
[Guest 1]: And therefore your space and your thought process

00:10:14.460 --> 00:10:16.460
[Guest 1]: And your decision making process

00:10:16.460 --> 00:10:19.460
[Guest 1]: So large organizations

00:10:19.460 --> 00:10:21.460
[Guest 1]: And everyone says Bennett Coleman started doing it

00:10:21.460 --> 00:10:24.460
[Guest 1]: But the fact of the matter Bennett did it most successfully

00:10:24.460 --> 00:10:26.460
[Guest 1]: And the others jumped in

00:10:26.460 --> 00:10:28.460
[Guest 1]: As they have jumped in with media net

00:10:28.460 --> 00:10:30.460
[Guest 1]: As they have jumped in with other things

00:10:30.460 --> 00:10:33.460
[Guest 1]: Paid news and all that kind of thing

00:10:33.460 --> 00:10:35.460
[Guest 1]: To be quite honest

00:10:35.460 --> 00:10:38.460
[Guest 1]: Sometimes if you read the Times of India today

00:10:38.460 --> 00:10:42.460
[Guest 1]: You get a far more comprehensive picture of what's happening in the city

00:10:42.460 --> 00:10:43.460
[Guest 1]: In the country and all that

00:10:43.460 --> 00:10:46.460
[Guest 1]: Because they have also invested in people

00:10:46.460 --> 00:10:50.460
[Guest 1]: And that you know that core strength hasn't disappeared

00:10:50.460 --> 00:10:52.460
[Guest 1]: But a lot of people have given that up

00:10:52.460 --> 00:10:54.460
[Amit Varma]: And started introducing these

00:10:54.460 --> 00:10:56.460
[Amit Varma]: As a columnist for the Times of India

00:10:56.460 --> 00:10:58.460
[Amit Varma]: I'm kind of glad you said that

00:10:58.460 --> 00:11:00.460
[Amit Varma]: But this shift therefore basically what happened was

00:11:00.460 --> 00:11:04.460
[Amit Varma]: That you are saying newspapers instead of producing journalism for readers

00:11:04.460 --> 00:11:06.460
[Amit Varma]: Started producing readers for advertisers

00:11:06.460 --> 00:11:08.460
[Guest 1]: Yes, yes, yes

00:11:08.460 --> 00:11:10.460
[Guest 1]: People have said publicly

00:11:10.460 --> 00:11:12.460
[Guest 1]: We are an ad platform

00:11:12.460 --> 00:11:16.460
[Guest 1]: This echoes what I think it was Beaverbrook

00:11:16.460 --> 00:11:18.460
[Guest 1]: Or somebody who said that you know

00:11:18.460 --> 00:11:19.460
[Amit Varma]: News is what you put

00:11:19.460 --> 00:11:21.460
[Amit Varma]: And was this driven by compulsion or greed?

00:11:21.460 --> 00:11:24.460
[Amit Varma]: Like did the earlier model not work for them to have to do this?

00:11:24.460 --> 00:11:25.460
[Amit Varma]: Or was this simply more

00:11:25.460 --> 00:11:26.460
[Guest 1]: Well look at it this way

00:11:26.460 --> 00:11:28.460
[Guest 1]: If you are chugging along very well

00:11:28.460 --> 00:11:30.460
[Guest 1]: And you are happy with a 40 crore turnover

00:11:30.460 --> 00:11:31.460
[Guest 1]: The model working

00:11:31.460 --> 00:11:32.460
[Guest 1]: Okay

00:11:32.460 --> 00:11:35.460
[Guest 1]: Because you are making a profit of 5 crores or 6 crores or whatever

00:11:35.460 --> 00:11:36.460
[Guest 1]: Okay

00:11:36.460 --> 00:11:37.460
[Guest 1]: You are a profitable organization

00:11:37.460 --> 00:11:39.460
[Guest 1]: Influence is fantastic

00:11:39.460 --> 00:11:41.460
[Guest 1]: Everyone says salam to the bosses

00:11:41.460 --> 00:11:45.460
[Guest 1]: But if you go from 40 crore turnover to 250

00:11:45.460 --> 00:11:47.460
[Guest 1]: Then 500

00:11:47.460 --> 00:11:50.460
[Guest 1]: Which model are you going to choose?

00:11:50.460 --> 00:11:51.460
[Amit Varma]: Right

00:11:51.460 --> 00:11:52.460
[Amit Varma]: As a businessman who

00:11:52.460 --> 00:11:54.460
[Guest 1]: You know you have to do right to your shareholders

00:11:54.460 --> 00:11:56.460
[Guest 1]: You are talking at this moment

00:11:56.460 --> 00:11:58.460
[Guest 1]: In the 80s I remember

00:11:58.460 --> 00:12:00.460
[Guest 1]: A multinational chief executive

00:12:00.460 --> 00:12:02.460
[Guest 1]: Had once said to a few of us

00:12:02.460 --> 00:12:07.460
[Guest 1]: Your publication is making more money than I am in this country

00:12:07.460 --> 00:12:09.460
[Guest 1]: And I have been here for 100 years

00:12:09.460 --> 00:12:12.460
[Guest 1]: So once that happened

00:12:12.460 --> 00:12:17.460
[Guest 1]: The journalist became the tool or the vehicle

00:12:17.460 --> 00:12:20.460
[Guest 1]: To deliver content

00:12:20.460 --> 00:12:23.460
[Guest 1]: And to give those this

00:12:23.460 --> 00:12:25.460
[Guest 1]: Now how does it show up in real terms?

00:12:25.460 --> 00:12:27.460
[Guest 1]: It shows up in the following way

00:12:27.460 --> 00:12:30.460
[Guest 1]: The morning when a family person

00:12:30.460 --> 00:12:32.460
[Guest 1]: You know husband, wife, whatever

00:12:32.460 --> 00:12:34.460
[Guest 1]: Gets up

00:12:34.460 --> 00:12:36.460
[Guest 1]: Reads the newspaper

00:12:36.460 --> 00:12:37.460
[Guest 1]: Has a cup of coffee

00:12:37.460 --> 00:12:39.460
[Guest 1]: Is about to tuck into the cereal

00:12:39.460 --> 00:12:43.460
[Guest 1]: And there is a photograph of somebody bleeding on the front page

00:12:43.460 --> 00:12:50.460
[Guest 1]: And that day either his or somebody else's product is in the solar space

00:12:50.460 --> 00:12:51.460
[Guest 1]: The company is not going to like it

00:12:51.460 --> 00:12:53.460
[Guest 1]: Because that's off-putting

00:12:53.460 --> 00:12:56.460
[Guest 1]: So you start feeding Pablum

00:12:56.460 --> 00:12:59.460
[Guest 1]: And you know keeping the reader happy

00:12:59.460 --> 00:13:01.460
[Guest 1]: The advertiser happy

00:13:01.460 --> 00:13:05.460
[Guest 1]: And generally creating this mythical, sweet, glowing world

00:13:05.460 --> 00:13:08.460
[Guest 1]: News naturally takes a hit

00:13:08.460 --> 00:13:11.460
[Guest 1]: And not all money gets funneled into news gathering

00:13:11.460 --> 00:13:14.460
[Guest 1]: Because some idiot will want to go to a village

00:13:14.460 --> 00:13:17.460
[Guest 1]: And come back with a story about an atrocity

00:13:17.460 --> 00:13:19.460
[Guest 1]: I know I am simplifying it

00:13:19.460 --> 00:13:20.460
[Guest 1]: But my bigger point is

00:13:20.460 --> 00:13:21.460
[Guest 1]: These things started having

00:13:21.460 --> 00:13:23.460
[Guest 1]: It's a long process

00:13:23.460 --> 00:13:25.460
[Guest 1]: What we are seeing today

00:13:25.460 --> 00:13:28.460
[Guest 1]: Has been speeded up in the last 4 years

00:13:28.460 --> 00:13:32.460
[Guest 1]: But it's a long process of devaluing the idea of good journalism

00:13:32.460 --> 00:13:34.460
[Amit Varma]: Peter, good time for me to turn to you

00:13:34.460 --> 00:13:36.460
[Amit Varma]: Siddharth has sort of been talking about how through the 70s

00:13:36.460 --> 00:13:38.460
[Amit Varma]: Until the 90s

00:13:38.460 --> 00:13:40.460
[Amit Varma]: The incentives for journalists changed

00:13:40.460 --> 00:13:42.460
[Amit Varma]: First of all the incentives changed

00:13:42.460 --> 00:13:44.460
[Amit Varma]: Because they were no longer the

00:13:44.460 --> 00:13:45.460
[Amit Varma]: Producing the main product

00:13:45.460 --> 00:13:46.460
[Amit Varma]: Which was the journalism

00:13:46.460 --> 00:13:48.460
[Amit Varma]: Which would you know attract readers to buy the newspaper

00:13:48.460 --> 00:13:50.460
[Amit Varma]: But the readers were the product

00:13:50.460 --> 00:13:51.460
[Amit Varma]: And they had to sort of you know

00:13:51.460 --> 00:13:54.460
[Amit Varma]: Everything had to be therefore done at the behest of advertisers

00:13:54.460 --> 00:13:55.460
[Amit Varma]: And so on

00:13:55.460 --> 00:13:58.460
[Amit Varma]: And this process became exacerbated so to say

00:13:58.460 --> 00:13:59.460
[Amit Varma]: When the business model changed

00:13:59.460 --> 00:14:01.460
[Amit Varma]: Where instead of relying on subscriptions

00:14:01.460 --> 00:14:02.460
[Amit Varma]: You start relying on advertising

00:14:02.460 --> 00:14:04.460
[Amit Varma]: Because it's far more profitable

00:14:04.460 --> 00:14:05.460
[Amit Varma]: Now as I was

00:14:05.460 --> 00:14:06.460
[Amit Varma]: You know we were chatting earlier

00:14:06.460 --> 00:14:08.460
[Amit Varma]: While we were on our way to the studio

00:14:08.460 --> 00:14:11.460
[Amit Varma]: I consider you a bit of an anomaly

00:14:11.460 --> 00:14:13.460
[Amit Varma]: Because even though you work as a senior editor

00:14:13.460 --> 00:14:14.460
[Amit Varma]: In an old media organization

00:14:14.460 --> 00:14:16.460
[Amit Varma]: I've always thought of you as someone

00:14:16.460 --> 00:14:19.460
[Amit Varma]: Who is right at the cutting edge of new media

00:14:19.460 --> 00:14:20.460
[Amit Varma]: You know I've known you from the time

00:14:20.460 --> 00:14:21.460
