[Guest 1]: I engage, I listen, that's my feedback. And what I also like to tell myself, I must respect

00:34:54.380 --> 00:34:58.260
[Guest 1]: my Twitter followers, and our readers, I owe it to them.

00:34:58.260 --> 00:35:00.140
[Guest 1]: I'm not talking down.

00:35:00.140 --> 00:35:05.180
[Amit Varma]: I am sharing I like to think and what you talk about, you know, the importance of the

00:35:05.180 --> 00:35:07.580
[Amit Varma]: editor and being a filter for content.

00:35:07.580 --> 00:35:10.340
[Amit Varma]: If you think about it in one way, all of us are our own filters.

00:35:10.340 --> 00:35:14.460
[Amit Varma]: That's what we use social media for, like what you will find on my Twitter feed will

00:35:14.460 --> 00:35:18.860
[Amit Varma]: be quite different from what is on yours or on Peter's because we've all already been

00:35:18.860 --> 00:35:19.860
[Guest 1]: our own.

00:35:19.860 --> 00:35:23.220
[Guest 1]: I can follow everybody and get a variety of views.

00:35:23.220 --> 00:35:29.860
[Guest 1]: I'm not saying send me this thing every morning, which only there are people who subscribe

00:35:29.860 --> 00:35:35.100
[Guest 1]: to let's say us, but they would subscribe to something that's on not us, except that

00:35:35.100 --> 00:35:43.060
[Guest 1]: subscribing to a rabidly right wing, lying website, fill in the blanks, yeah.

00:35:43.060 --> 00:35:44.500
[Guest 1]: Because I know you have a huge audience.

00:35:44.500 --> 00:35:48.100
[Guest 1]: So I don't want to get into legal issues, you're welcome to say whatever the hell you

00:35:48.100 --> 00:35:49.100
[Guest 1]: want.

00:35:49.100 --> 00:35:54.620
[Guest 1]: But that is not the counter to that is not the wire is not that the counter to the wire

00:35:54.620 --> 00:36:01.780
[Guest 1]: is to say, look, I like you, but I think your views are too extreme, or too not to my liking.

00:36:01.780 --> 00:36:03.660
[Amit Varma]: I will read something that balances.

00:36:03.660 --> 00:36:07.340
[Amit Varma]: So here's whatever it may be, here's a subject I want to explore.

00:36:07.340 --> 00:36:08.340
[Amit Varma]: How do you make money?

00:36:08.340 --> 00:36:09.900
[Amit Varma]: How does journalism today make money?

00:36:09.900 --> 00:36:12.100
[Amit Varma]: Is the wire profitable, if I may ask?

00:36:12.100 --> 00:36:14.020
[Guest 1]: Or is there a path to profitability?

00:36:14.020 --> 00:36:18.060
[Guest 1]: So we there is no question of profitability, because we are donation led, right?

00:36:18.060 --> 00:36:19.660
[Guest 1]: We are not for profit.

00:36:19.660 --> 00:36:28.740
[Guest 1]: We began with three of us putting in I say this, we had a lot of things lacking, we are

00:36:28.740 --> 00:36:30.380
[Guest 1]: just three lakhs.

00:36:30.380 --> 00:36:33.500
[Guest 1]: That's all one lakh, one lakh, one lakh, that's all.

00:36:33.500 --> 00:36:37.880
[Guest 1]: And for months, we never took a salary, we worked out of each other's homes.

00:36:37.880 --> 00:36:42.660
[Guest 1]: When I went to Delhi, I stayed with my friends, they came down, they stayed with me.

00:36:42.660 --> 00:36:44.180
[Guest 1]: That's how we managed.

00:36:44.180 --> 00:36:50.500
[Guest 1]: Some old karma must have played a role because for about 10 months, or 12 months, we never

00:36:50.500 --> 00:36:52.660
[Guest 1]: paid people.

00:36:52.660 --> 00:36:59.900
[Guest 1]: And now we do but because we just called in favor left, right and center, halfway through,

00:36:59.900 --> 00:37:03.020
[Guest 1]: people realize this was a platform worth writing on.

00:37:03.020 --> 00:37:05.500
[Guest 1]: So more people started writing.

00:37:05.500 --> 00:37:10.380
[Guest 1]: After about eight months, a high net worth individual came to us and says, I'd like to

00:37:10.380 --> 00:37:11.620
[Guest 1]: give you some money.

00:37:11.620 --> 00:37:15.780
[Guest 1]: He was turned out to be super generous gave us 50 lakhs.

00:37:15.780 --> 00:37:20.140
[Guest 1]: And since then, we've got money from foundations from grants.

00:37:20.140 --> 00:37:25.820
[Guest 1]: And now of course, we have a very active online donation program.

00:37:25.820 --> 00:37:30.740
[Amit Varma]: So there's no question of profit, but we are always short of what we want.

00:37:30.740 --> 00:37:34.900
[Amit Varma]: But here's my thing, you know, what you just said, both gives me great hope and also great

00:37:34.900 --> 00:37:39.660
[Amit Varma]: despair, great hope, because it's wonderful to know that there are people for whom journalism

00:37:39.660 --> 00:37:41.980
[Amit Varma]: is a labor of love, and they will do it no matter what.

00:37:41.980 --> 00:37:45.620
[Amit Varma]: And, you know, they will fight the odds to do it like you guys started from your homes.

00:37:45.620 --> 00:37:50.020
[Amit Varma]: But it also gives me despair that one has to depend on the passion of individuals and

00:37:50.020 --> 00:37:56.540
[Amit Varma]: on, you know, the magnanimity of philanthropists here and there, and the common donor, rather

00:37:56.540 --> 00:37:58.580
[Amit Varma]: than actually be able to make money from it.

00:37:58.580 --> 00:37:59.980
[Amit Varma]: And that makes me very sad.

00:37:59.980 --> 00:38:04.460
[Amit Varma]: And my question here, Peter is, and we were discussing this earlier, is that, look, I

00:38:04.460 --> 00:38:09.020
[Amit Varma]: think everyone who reads Viyar or who reads Kroll, another excellent magazine, or Pragati

00:38:09.020 --> 00:38:13.780
[Amit Varma]: Mayur magazine, everyone who reads any of these publications is paying for it, they're

00:38:13.780 --> 00:38:16.540
[Amit Varma]: paying for it, because they're spending a certain amount of time on it.

00:38:16.540 --> 00:38:21.420
[Amit Varma]: Time is money, there's opportunity cost, except there's no way for the publisher to capture

00:38:21.420 --> 00:38:22.420
[Amit Varma]: that value.

00:38:22.420 --> 00:38:26.500
[Amit Varma]: Now, earlier, the old school value was you bring out a newspaper, readers read it, you

00:38:26.500 --> 00:38:29.740
[Amit Varma]: capture that through advertising, that is clearly not working.

00:38:29.740 --> 00:38:33.540
[Amit Varma]: You know, you've worked with Network 18 for many years, and now with The Hindu, advertising

00:38:33.540 --> 00:38:38.140
[Amit Varma]: no longer is enough to make money of digital media, subscriptions, really, I believe the

00:38:38.140 --> 00:38:42.500
[Amit Varma]: Ken is doing very well and more power to them, but haven't really taken off to that extent.

00:38:42.500 --> 00:38:46.740
[Amit Varma]: How do you make money with journalism is my question to both of you.

00:38:46.740 --> 00:38:53.820
[Guest 2]: Okay, so, you know, it wasn't just the subscription price that killed that caused the introduction

00:38:53.820 --> 00:38:56.300
[Guest 2]: price that caused problems.

00:38:56.300 --> 00:39:01.340
[Guest 2]: What came up was that no one, I think, from the beginning, learned how to deal with the

00:39:01.340 --> 00:39:04.020
[Guest 2]: internet.

00:39:04.020 --> 00:39:09.580
[Guest 2]: Because even if you're paying two bucks for your newspaper, and I could get the same thing

00:39:09.580 --> 00:39:15.820
[Guest 2]: online for free, paying the cost of my internet subscription, which was pretty high at that

00:39:15.820 --> 00:39:19.140
[Guest 2]: point, you know, prices have dropped there.

00:39:19.140 --> 00:39:26.660
[Guest 2]: But we got accustomed all over the world, for the internet to give us stuff for free.

00:39:26.660 --> 00:39:30.020
[Guest 2]: And if the internet didn't give us stuff for free, if somebody tried to, you know, charge

00:39:30.020 --> 00:39:32.820
[Guest 2]: you money for it, there were others were giving it free.

00:39:32.820 --> 00:39:37.420
[Guest 2]: So in a similar way that you couldn't combat the two rupee invitation price, and keep your

00:39:37.420 --> 00:39:42.300
[Guest 2]: money because the moment someone else succumbs, you have alternatives who are giving you,

00:39:42.300 --> 00:39:47.220
[Guest 2]: you know, your news at lower rates, then the guy who's charging higher will say okay, fine,

00:39:47.220 --> 00:39:50.340
[Guest 2]: we don't, even though that's, you know, a trivial amount, it's the cost of a Vodapower

00:39:50.340 --> 00:39:54.740
[Guest 2]: at that point, or whatever it is, you would still go to the cheaper alternative.

00:39:54.740 --> 00:40:02.860
[Guest 2]: Now, the problem is, I don't think any of us in the traditional media have really learned

00:40:02.860 --> 00:40:07.500
[Guest 2]: how to, or what we think enough about the internet.

00:40:07.500 --> 00:40:12.380
[Guest 2]: I think that in India, we have had a bit of a cushion.

00:40:12.380 --> 00:40:21.700
[Guest 2]: In the more developed parts of the world, newspapers closing down, shutting shop, slashing

00:40:21.700 --> 00:40:26.020
[Guest 2]: the sizes of their newsrooms and all of that.

00:40:26.020 --> 00:40:29.140
[Guest 2]: In India, we have a few fortunate things happening.

00:40:29.140 --> 00:40:34.980
[Guest 2]: One is that we're still a poor country, we're still a country with a large amount of a large

00:40:34.980 --> 00:40:36.740
[Guest 2]: gap in literacy.

00:40:36.740 --> 00:40:39.420
[Guest 2]: There are new literates coming in every day.

00:40:39.420 --> 00:40:42.420
[Guest 2]: We're not a mature market in that sense, right?

00:40:42.420 --> 00:40:46.220
[Guest 2]: So when new people are coming in every day, they want something to consume, in terms they

00:40:46.220 --> 00:40:49.420
[Guest 2]: want information, they want to be able to read it.

00:40:49.420 --> 00:40:55.560
[Guest 2]: And so we have growth, it has given us the illusion that the media is continuing to grow.

00:40:55.560 --> 00:40:57.420
[Guest 2]: Because there are new people coming in.

00:40:57.420 --> 00:41:03.380
[Guest 2]: And when you come in newly to literacy, you're not going straight to literature, right?

00:41:03.380 --> 00:41:08.300
[Guest 2]: You look at functional information first, where do I get what is the price of X?

00:41:08.300 --> 00:41:13.540
[Guest 2]: So where do I get good sales for, you know, find my markets for my produce, find out the

00:41:13.540 --> 00:41:16.580
[Guest 2]: basic information and then the media delivers that.

00:41:16.580 --> 00:41:21.020
[Guest 2]: But we have, we could have been using this time, I think, broadly in the Indian media

00:41:21.020 --> 00:41:24.860
[Guest 2]: to figure out how to find paying models.

00:41:24.860 --> 00:41:31.420
[Guest 2]: Whether it is as Siddharth was talking about, where you've decided that your funding is

00:41:31.420 --> 00:41:38.900
[Guest 2]: going to come from philanthropists and donors, or the Ken model, which is entirely subscription

00:41:38.900 --> 00:41:44.380
[Guest 2]: based or the hybrid models or some other stuff we haven't thought of yet.

00:41:44.380 --> 00:41:45.940
[Guest 2]: How are you going to deliver that content?

00:41:45.940 --> 00:41:49.620
[Guest 2]: We should have been having these conversations and been thinking about it for years now.

00:41:49.620 --> 00:41:58.340
[Guest 2]: We haven't because we've been growing in smaller and smaller, you know, jumps, but we've been

00:41:58.340 --> 00:42:01.500
[Guest 2]: still continuing to grow.

00:42:01.500 --> 00:42:06.620
[Guest 2]: The fragmentation that we were talking about, all the other stuff that comes in, you know,

00:42:06.620 --> 00:42:09.220
[Guest 2]: just one little point out there, we're talking about Twitter and everything and the things

00:42:09.220 --> 00:42:14.220
[Guest 2]: that all the Twitter and early blogs and everything, all the big accounts, mainstream media noticed

00:42:14.220 --> 00:42:19.820
[Guest 2]: them, gave them that and, you know, your credibility came from having been written about the Tsunami

00:42:19.820 --> 00:42:25.060
[Guest 2]: Help blog came, got credibility from being featured in XYZ and then the New York Times

00:42:25.060 --> 00:42:31.540
[Guest 2]: picking it up and then suddenly we were world famous for like five days, all of that stuff.

00:42:31.540 --> 00:42:36.820
[Guest 2]: There's still a huge amount of power in the media is what that tells me.

00:42:36.820 --> 00:42:43.060
[Guest 2]: Things are being discussed in opposition to the media, but you're still opposing that

00:42:43.060 --> 00:42:44.060
[Guest 2]: thing that's there.

00:42:44.060 --> 00:42:46.140
[Guest 2]: It's still important enough to oppose.

00:42:46.140 --> 00:42:52.140
[Guest 2]: So that gives me in a strange kind of way, hope that enough people take enough time to

00:42:52.140 --> 00:42:57.100
[Guest 2]: combat and debunk or fight against what they see as the oppression.

00:42:57.100 --> 00:42:58.460
[Amit Varma]: And some value in it.

00:42:58.460 --> 00:42:59.460
[Amit Varma]: That's the more important.

00:42:59.460 --> 00:43:02.460
[Guest 2]: It's because they see value in it that they think it's important enough to counter.

00:43:02.460 --> 00:43:06.500
[Guest 2]: Now, even the ones who are saying this is all bloody fake news are still taking the

00:43:06.500 --> 00:43:10.100
[Guest 2]: trouble to say that it is fake news.

00:43:10.100 --> 00:43:11.340
[Guest 2]: Okay.

00:43:11.340 --> 00:43:13.620
[Guest 2]: It's worth attention.

00:43:13.620 --> 00:43:18.500
[Guest 2]: And that in a strange way actually gives me hope that you still think it's important enough

00:43:18.500 --> 00:43:23.220
[Guest 2]: to fight that the old fashioned battles are still being fought in new media kind of ways

00:43:23.220 --> 00:43:27.100
[Guest 2]: that someone with the solid credentials of Siddharth and the team out there are still

00:43:27.100 --> 00:43:29.780
[Guest 2]: out there being able to deliver this stuff.

00:43:29.780 --> 00:43:33.900
[Amit Varma]: This does give me hope, but I'll tell you where the gap is and what the dilemma is.

00:43:33.900 --> 00:43:37.360
[Amit Varma]: Let's say that it gives both of us hope that someone like Pratik Sinha of Alt News is doing

00:43:37.360 --> 00:43:38.360
[Amit Varma]: what he's doing.

00:43:38.360 --> 00:43:41.500
[Amit Varma]: It's just magnificent, which is basically debunking fake news all the time.

00:43:41.500 --> 00:43:46.300
[Amit Varma]: It also gives me great hope that he has so many followers and Alt News has so many readers.

00:43:46.300 --> 00:43:49.660
[Amit Varma]: What worries me is that they are not supremely profitable.

00:43:49.660 --> 00:43:51.020
[Amit Varma]: That is sort of where the gap is.

00:43:51.020 --> 00:43:55.540
[Amit Varma]: And I understand that some of it is because of inertia in our mindsets like the, you know,

00:43:55.540 --> 00:43:59.180
[Amit Varma]: a lot of newspapers sell simply because I'm used to the daily newspaper coming to my house

00:43:59.180 --> 00:44:00.180
[Amit Varma]: and I just don't cancel.

00:44:00.180 --> 00:44:05.580
[Guest 1]: Also, they also sell because advertising in newspaper is also information.

00:44:05.580 --> 00:44:06.580
[Guest 1]: Okay.

00:44:06.580 --> 00:44:07.580
[Amit Varma]: It's very important to understand.

00:44:07.580 --> 00:44:10.100
[Guest 1]: But do people buy newspapers for advertising?

00:44:10.100 --> 00:44:15.860
[Guest 1]: 40% of a newspaper buyer is because of classifieds, even today, because we don't have Craigslist.

00:44:15.860 --> 00:44:16.860
[Guest 1]: Right.

00:44:16.860 --> 00:44:22.660
[Guest 1]: But a lot of people still want to buy and sell cars via that rather than the digital

00:44:22.660 --> 00:44:23.660
[Guest 1]: world.

00:44:23.660 --> 00:44:31.940
[Guest 1]: And, you know, large advertising display is also this read by a lot of people.

00:44:31.940 --> 00:44:37.340
[Guest 1]: So advertising is a critical part of the information package, which is really interesting.

00:44:37.340 --> 00:44:39.700
[Amit Varma]: Those are the two kinds of inertia I was mentioning.

00:44:39.700 --> 00:44:42.940
[Amit Varma]: One is that people who wouldn't otherwise read newspapers still pay for them in one

00:44:42.940 --> 00:44:44.420
[Amit Varma]: way or the other.

00:44:44.420 --> 00:44:47.860
[Amit Varma]: And the other one is that in the early days of the internet, no one wanted to pay for

00:44:47.860 --> 00:44:48.860
[Amit Varma]: anything even we didn't.

00:44:48.860 --> 00:44:53.060
[Amit Varma]: And part of the reason is a friction in payment, who's going to give you a credit card detail?

00:44:53.060 --> 00:44:55.140
[Amit Varma]: How do you make micropayments happen?

00:44:55.140 --> 00:44:57.220
[Amit Varma]: Most of that friction has actually gone away now.

00:44:57.220 --> 00:44:59.860
[Amit Varma]: And you can set up systems to do it really easily.

00:44:59.860 --> 00:45:03.020
[Amit Varma]: And yet, that model hasn't really taken off.

00:45:03.020 --> 00:45:04.020
[Guest 1]: No.

00:45:04.020 --> 00:45:08.620
[Guest 1]: So I think part of your answer is in your question.

00:45:08.620 --> 00:45:15.020
[Guest 1]: And that is that I can point out several things today which were unheard of and, you know,

00:45:15.020 --> 00:45:17.020
[Guest 1]: people are skeptical about.

00:45:17.020 --> 00:45:20.540
[Guest 1]: A lot of newspapers, even in India, are now selling their archives.

00:45:20.540 --> 00:45:22.580
[Guest 1]: You have to subscribe for the archives.

00:45:22.580 --> 00:45:27.860
[Guest 1]: I think your own newspaper, The Hindu, after seven days, you need to pay to read anything

00:45:27.860 --> 00:45:32.180
[Guest 1]: before seven days, if I'm not mistaken, or register at least.

00:45:32.180 --> 00:45:33.340
[Guest 1]: Payment is going to come.

00:45:33.340 --> 00:45:35.420
[Guest 1]: You can't read the Economic Political Weekly.

00:45:35.420 --> 00:45:36.740
[Guest 1]: A lot of people want to read it.

00:45:36.740 --> 00:45:40.140
[Guest 1]: You have to subscribe for the online version.

00:45:40.140 --> 00:45:43.820
[Guest 1]: So everyone said nobody pays.

00:45:43.820 --> 00:45:49.820
[Guest 1]: The New York Times had a huge flop when they tried to introduce payment in the early days.

00:45:49.820 --> 00:45:53.220
[Guest 1]: Then they said, OK, columnist is payment, the rest is free.

00:45:53.220 --> 00:45:57.180
[Guest 1]: Now only three articles or five articles or whatever.

00:45:57.180 --> 00:46:02.540
[Guest 1]: And all the legacy brands around the world in every country, whether it's, you know,

00:46:02.540 --> 00:46:08.940
[Guest 1]: Spiegel, or whether it is Le Monde, or whether it's The Economist, The Times, in London,

00:46:08.940 --> 00:46:10.260
[Guest 1]: The Guardian, not.

00:46:10.260 --> 00:46:15.340
[Guest 1]: But everywhere else, you've got to pay.

00:46:15.340 --> 00:46:16.660
[Guest 1]: Business Standard is trying it here.

00:46:16.660 --> 00:46:19.060
[Guest 1]: I don't know how successful they are.

00:46:19.060 --> 00:46:22.420
[Guest 1]: But then Business Standard's own columnists post their articles on their blog.

00:46:22.420 --> 00:46:24.380
[Guest 1]: So you are getting something.

00:46:24.380 --> 00:46:26.100
[Guest 1]: But it's going to change.

00:46:26.100 --> 00:46:27.700
[Guest 1]: It's going to definitely change.

00:46:27.700 --> 00:46:32.420
[Guest 1]: Who thought donor-led news media would take off?

00:46:32.420 --> 00:46:34.900
[Guest 1]: Now there are, as you said, hybrid model.

00:46:34.900 --> 00:46:38.260
[Guest 1]: There are at least two or three people who said they call it subscribe.

00:46:38.260 --> 00:46:42.980
[Amit Varma]: So can we see the day when The Wire and Alt News are hugely successful by themselves and

00:46:42.980 --> 00:46:43.980
[Guest 1]: don't need donors?

00:46:43.980 --> 00:46:48.660
[Guest 1]: So the model for hugely successful is, you know, flexible.

00:46:48.660 --> 00:46:53.700
[Guest 1]: I would say we are not going to become a 5,000 crore company anytime soon.

00:46:53.700 --> 00:47:00.780
[Guest 1]: But if I can get, say, 35% of that influence, 50% of that influence, and a piece in The

00:47:00.780 --> 00:47:06.340
[Guest 1]: Wire gets the attention of policymakers, I think we've got it.

00:47:06.340 --> 00:47:12.820
[Guest 1]: So, you know, I would love to make 5,000 crores and probably will put 4,999 crores into news

00:47:12.820 --> 00:47:13.820
[Guest 1]: gathering.

00:47:13.820 --> 00:47:16.100
[Guest 1]: As a promoter, I don't get anything.

00:47:16.100 --> 00:47:18.520
[Guest 1]: My salary is low and my dividends zero.

00:47:18.520 --> 00:47:20.660
[Guest 1]: So there's no money for me.

00:47:20.660 --> 00:47:22.340
[Guest 1]: But I would love to do it.

00:47:22.340 --> 00:47:29.900
[Guest 1]: Who would have thought that Vinod Dua, long forgotten, resurrected by us, in the sense

00:47:29.900 --> 00:47:36.940
[Guest 1]: that mainstream channels wouldn't touch him, would have a confirmed subscriber base on

00:47:36.940 --> 00:47:39.260
[Guest 1]: YouTube of 700,000.

00:47:39.260 --> 00:47:41.020
[Guest 1]: And that's a remarkable show.

00:47:41.020 --> 00:47:42.020
[Guest 1]: Right?

00:47:42.020 --> 00:47:43.860
[Guest 1]: 700,000 is our YouTube channel.

00:47:43.860 --> 00:47:46.900
[Guest 1]: We are people who know nothing about that world.

00:47:46.900 --> 00:47:48.060
[Amit Varma]: Does he make a lot of money?

00:47:48.060 --> 00:47:49.460
[Amit Varma]: Does he monetize that?

00:47:49.460 --> 00:47:50.460
[Guest 1]: Of course not.

00:47:50.460 --> 00:47:51.460
[Guest 1]: We get advertising.

00:47:51.460 --> 00:47:52.460
[Guest 1]: Yes.

00:47:52.460 --> 00:47:53.460
[Guest 1]: YouTube gives us advertising.

00:47:53.460 --> 00:47:54.700
[Guest 1]: YouTube does.

00:47:54.700 --> 00:47:57.580
[Guest 1]: It's very easy to become a YouTube one put advertising.

00:47:57.580 --> 00:48:00.300
[Guest 1]: I mean, they're very, very cooperative.

00:48:00.300 --> 00:48:02.780
[Guest 1]: But we don't have an ad manager.

00:48:02.780 --> 00:48:07.120
[Guest 1]: And we don't have a show sponsor on our channel.

00:48:07.120 --> 00:48:09.600
[Guest 1]: And that's because we can't afford an advertising manager.

00:48:09.600 --> 00:48:15.660
[Guest 1]: But tomorrow when we can afford an ad manager, that person will get sponsorships for that.

00:48:15.660 --> 00:48:18.380
[Guest 1]: I'll give you another tiny example.

00:48:18.380 --> 00:48:22.140
[Guest 1]: You know, these summits held by newspapers and all that kind of thing, right?

00:48:22.140 --> 00:48:26.620
[Guest 1]: And there are a lot of these award shows, cocktail parties, promotions, brand promotions,

00:48:26.620 --> 00:48:28.740
[Guest 1]: all kinds of innovative names.

00:48:28.740 --> 00:48:35.860
[Guest 1]: I think almost all maybe barring a few here and there are free events, right?

00:48:35.860 --> 00:48:39.500
[Guest 1]: Of course, there are tickets for certain shows, certain summits and all that.

00:48:39.500 --> 00:48:43.460
[Guest 1]: We've been holding small ticketed events, small.

00:48:43.460 --> 00:48:49.460
[Guest 1]: Arun Chori talks to Karan Thapar, 800-700 people, tickets sold at something like the

00:48:49.460 --> 00:48:52.420
[Guest 1]: first five rows or something 2000 rupees.

00:48:52.420 --> 00:48:53.420
[Guest 1]: We made money on it.

00:48:53.420 --> 00:48:59.900
[Guest 1]: Who would have thought, Arun Chori in Delhi, you know, so these are tiny drops in the ocean,

00:48:59.900 --> 00:49:02.820
[Guest 1]: but things do change.

00:49:02.820 --> 00:49:06.500
[Guest 1]: You know, there are websites which are trying the subscription model, they may not succeed

00:49:06.500 --> 00:49:07.500
[Guest 1]: today.

00:49:07.500 --> 00:49:14.340
[Guest 1]: They may tomorrow, some are trying the embedded advertising model, some are getting so things

00:49:14.340 --> 00:49:15.340
[Amit Varma]: are changing definitely.

00:49:15.340 --> 00:49:17.180
[Amit Varma]: We are innovative enough, we'll figure it out.

00:49:17.180 --> 00:49:18.380
[Amit Varma]: All this will work.

00:49:18.380 --> 00:49:19.380
[Amit Varma]: Yes.

00:49:19.380 --> 00:49:23.580
[Amit Varma]: Well, you know, let's move on to from the commerce to let me ask you guys about the

00:49:23.580 --> 00:49:27.900
[Amit Varma]: media climate in India, given what's happening politically, given that there is this interplay

00:49:27.900 --> 00:49:33.220
[Amit Varma]: between money and power, that does affect the way the mainstream media reports on things.

00:49:33.220 --> 00:49:38.140
[Amit Varma]: For example, you pointed out earlier that Jay Shah's case on the wire was not reported

00:49:38.140 --> 00:49:39.140
[Amit Varma]: by any of the mainstream.

00:49:39.140 --> 00:49:43.820
[Guest 1]: No, it was reported the next day, but the emphasis was on the case that he was to file

00:49:43.820 --> 00:49:44.820
[Amit Varma]: on Monday morning.

00:49:44.820 --> 00:49:45.820
[Amit Varma]: Right.

00:49:45.820 --> 00:49:47.860
[Guest 1]: And no one called you for a comment?

00:49:47.860 --> 00:49:52.180
[Guest 1]: I don't think anyone called and used a comment in any substantive way.

00:49:52.180 --> 00:49:58.300
[Guest 1]: And I also, I mean, you know, others may have got private phone calls, I did not get a single

00:49:58.300 --> 00:50:00.300
[Guest 1]: call of solidarity.

00:50:00.300 --> 00:50:02.980
[Guest 1]: And I've been in the business for a while.

00:50:02.980 --> 00:50:06.820
[Guest 1]: So the big newspapers reported it.

00:50:06.820 --> 00:50:10.260
[Guest 1]: And you've seen with Rafal, right, right.

00:50:10.260 --> 00:50:16.600
[Guest 1]: Olan contradicts Mr. Modi's statement is the headline, obvious headline, it should be.

00:50:16.600 --> 00:50:22.780
[Guest 1]: And it says that it sparks off a, you know, crossfire, a political crossfire in India.

00:50:22.780 --> 00:50:23.780
[Amit Varma]: That's hardly the news.

00:50:23.780 --> 00:50:27.260
[Amit Varma]: Yeah, I was shocked to see one of the headlines in one of the mainstream newspapers, I won't

00:50:27.260 --> 00:50:28.260
[Amit Varma]: take the name.

00:50:28.260 --> 00:50:30.380
[Amit Varma]: But we are recording this, by the way, on September 24.

00:50:30.380 --> 00:50:31.620
[Amit Varma]: So it'll come out a bit later.

00:50:31.620 --> 00:50:36.180
[Amit Varma]: But it's in the context of what's going on now, I'm just letting the listeners know.

00:50:36.180 --> 00:50:37.180
[Amit Varma]: And does this worry you?

00:50:37.180 --> 00:50:39.180
[Guest 1]: Yes, of course, it worries me.

00:50:39.180 --> 00:50:41.500
[Guest 1]: I'm a practicing professional journalist.

00:50:41.500 --> 00:50:45.220
[Guest 1]: I think my duty is to my readers all the time.

00:50:45.220 --> 00:50:52.940
[Guest 1]: You know, this sounds like a grand mission statement, but it's there embedded in my.

00:50:52.940 --> 00:51:00.540
[Guest 1]: So of course, it worries me that the media state in India at the moment.

00:51:00.540 --> 00:51:03.460
[Guest 1]: As I said, I'm a professional journalist.

00:51:03.460 --> 00:51:08.140
[Guest 1]: I think of my reader, I'm not constantly motivated by what the reader may feel.

00:51:08.140 --> 00:51:12.340
[Guest 1]: I don't want to be second guess, or second guess that reader of mine.

00:51:12.340 --> 00:51:15.340
[Guest 1]: I think she's intelligent, articulate.

00:51:15.340 --> 00:51:19.580
[Guest 1]: And if she comes to us definitely curious and eager to know what's going on.

00:51:19.580 --> 00:51:29.180
[Guest 1]: But I do instinctively, intuitively realize and understand that ultimately, all this is

00:51:29.180 --> 00:51:32.860
[Guest 1]: to bring my reader up to speed with what's happening.

00:51:32.860 --> 00:51:37.940
[Guest 1]: And when I see that reader being taken for granted with this kind of thing, how many

00:51:37.940 --> 00:51:42.460
[Guest 1]: people have turned around and told you that, you know, we don't trust the big media anymore.

00:51:42.460 --> 00:51:47.420
[Guest 1]: Some have said it because it's kind of a, you know, everyone says it.

00:51:47.420 --> 00:51:50.060
[Guest 1]: Some say it because it's not meeting their requirement.

00:51:50.060 --> 00:51:55.060
[Guest 1]: But some say it because they're not getting what they think is authentic information.

00:51:55.060 --> 00:52:00.180
[Guest 1]: If we are, of course, called all kinds of things, you know, Rahul Gandhi is funding

00:52:00.180 --> 00:52:02.020
[Guest 1]: us and all that.

00:52:02.020 --> 00:52:05.860
[Guest 1]: If they were funding us, we'd be in a 10 times better situation.

00:52:05.860 --> 00:52:08.020
[Guest 1]: We're hand to mouth, basically.

00:52:08.020 --> 00:52:11.300
[Guest 1]: But yes, it does worry me.

00:52:11.300 --> 00:52:15.260
[Guest 1]: You know, I when I speak to students, I'm reminded of something that I may have read

00:52:15.260 --> 00:52:16.260
[Guest 1]: years ago.

00:52:16.260 --> 00:52:19.700
[Guest 1]: By the way, I was never told about these things by any senior.

00:52:19.700 --> 00:52:24.380
[Guest 1]: There was no mission statement in my organization, or anywhere else.

00:52:24.380 --> 00:52:26.580
[Guest 1]: But it gets into your system.

00:52:26.580 --> 00:52:32.540
[Guest 1]: But I remember reading, I think it was HL Menken, who said, you know, journalism is

00:52:32.540 --> 00:52:36.500
[Guest 1]: about comforting the afflicted and afflicting the comfortable.

00:52:36.500 --> 00:52:40.140
[Guest 1]: And I think we are comforting the comfortable.

00:52:40.140 --> 00:52:42.460
[Amit Varma]: And afflicting the afflicted by ignoring them.

00:52:42.460 --> 00:52:49.180
[Guest 1]: But that too, but you know, all the stuff that is appearing is about so and so IIT topper

00:52:49.180 --> 00:52:51.300
[Guest 1]: gets this salary.

00:52:51.300 --> 00:52:55.900
[Guest 1]: This is kind of mollycoddling your reader with all kind of good news.

00:52:55.900 --> 00:52:59.020
[Guest 1]: Indian cricket is covered as though we are the greatest in the world.

00:52:59.020 --> 00:53:02.060
[Guest 1]: And I'm sorry, we're not.

00:53:02.060 --> 00:53:07.260
[Guest 1]: India lost, England did not win alone, we lost badly.

00:53:07.260 --> 00:53:08.260
[Guest 1]: I'll end on this.

00:53:08.260 --> 00:53:14.580
[Guest 1]: There's a fantastic headline in one of the papers in Shekhar Kapoor's film, Elizabeth

00:53:14.580 --> 00:53:17.300
[Guest 1]: went to the Oscars.

00:53:17.300 --> 00:53:23.220
[Guest 1]: And it's a foreign production with a foreign cast with a director who happened to be of

00:53:23.220 --> 00:53:25.740
[Guest 1]: Indian ethnic origin.

00:53:25.740 --> 00:53:33.620
[Guest 1]: And it lost in the mainstream, they got only one or none awards in the Oscars.

00:53:33.620 --> 00:53:38.700
[Guest 1]: And the headline in this paper in Delhi was, and the Oscars goes to apartheid.

00:53:38.700 --> 00:53:44.040
[Guest 1]: I mean, look at the sheer idiocy about this statement.

00:53:44.040 --> 00:53:46.420
[Guest 1]: You have firstly no idea what apartheid is.

00:53:46.420 --> 00:53:49.060
[Guest 1]: And secondly, is it racism?

00:53:49.060 --> 00:53:50.500
[Guest 1]: Or were they better films?

00:53:50.500 --> 00:53:51.900
[Guest 1]: Is the world against us?

00:53:51.900 --> 00:53:57.980
[Guest 1]: I mean, this sense of victimhood, this sense of wanting to win all the time.

00:53:57.980 --> 00:53:59.460
[Amit Varma]: Victimhood and populism kind of go together.

00:53:59.460 --> 00:54:03.540
[Guest 1]: This is, I'm sorry to say, Deutschland ber alles all over again, you know.

00:54:03.540 --> 00:54:09.020
[Amit Varma]: So I'll end this episode by, that can't be your last word on the subject.

00:54:09.020 --> 00:54:13.620
[Amit Varma]: I'm going to end this episode by asking you guys one question with two parts each, which

00:54:13.620 --> 00:54:18.380
[Amit Varma]: is what makes you hopeful and what makes you despair about the state of the media in India

00:54:18.380 --> 00:54:19.380
[Amit Varma]: today?

00:54:19.380 --> 00:54:20.880
[Guest 2]: Peter, let's start with you.

00:54:20.880 --> 00:54:28.900
[Guest 2]: The hope is that we're having these conversations, for instance, you work with Pragati, which

00:54:28.900 --> 00:54:32.340
[Guest 2]: is a startup in that sense, it was a relaunch of the magazine.

00:54:32.340 --> 00:54:34.180
[Guest 2]: You're finding ways to fund it.

00:54:34.180 --> 00:54:39.140
[Guest 2]: You're sitting here and doing this podcast and have been doing it for a while, have built

00:54:39.140 --> 00:54:41.640
[Guest 2]: up readership and are not making money on it.

00:54:41.640 --> 00:54:44.700
[Guest 2]: But you're doing it to build an audience.

00:54:44.700 --> 00:54:51.020
[Guest 2]: Siddharth and the team that he's working with have found ways to deliver old fashioned journalism

00:54:51.020 --> 00:54:53.200
[Guest 2]: in new ways.

00:54:53.200 --> 00:54:58.660
[Guest 2]: And as I was saying just a few minutes ago, that people find the media still worth fighting

00:54:58.660 --> 00:55:04.580
[Guest 2]: with or against is actually makes me optimistic because there's enough power there.

00:55:04.580 --> 00:55:11.500
[Guest 2]: Those are all, I see young people, there are the young people who will be happy to reproduce

00:55:11.500 --> 00:55:13.860
[Guest 2]: press releases for sure.

00:55:13.860 --> 00:55:18.820
[Guest 2]: But I've seen a huge number of young people who are still burning with that desire to

00:55:18.820 --> 00:55:23.060
[Guest 2]: go out there and tell truths, find out, dig.

00:55:23.060 --> 00:55:31.820
[Guest 2]: Young people in my organization, interns who are willing to, you know, we had a kid in

00:55:31.820 --> 00:55:34.420
[Guest 2]: here who didn't even do a one month internship.

00:55:34.420 --> 00:55:39.300
[Guest 2]: She interned with us for six months, doing a full time college course, just so she could

00:55:39.300 --> 00:55:43.740
[Guest 2]: get experience and for free, as in she wasn't even getting paid expenses.

00:55:43.740 --> 00:55:46.840
[Guest 2]: All these things give me optimism for the future.

00:55:46.840 --> 00:55:52.860
[Guest 2]: What makes me despair is this entire thing of this, again, internet enabled, I guess,

00:55:52.860 --> 00:55:57.900
[Guest 2]: in some ways, the polarizations that have happened, that we will retreat and be content

00:55:57.900 --> 00:56:03.100
[Guest 2]: to have our opinions confirmed rather than challenged.

00:56:03.100 --> 00:56:09.860
[Guest 2]: You know, for me, I have always, I mean, this is doing what you, I know you don't like very

00:56:09.860 --> 00:56:15.900
[Guest 2]: much virtue signaling, but for me, conversations like this are bloody interesting, because

00:56:15.900 --> 00:56:20.100
[Guest 2]: I'm learning about things that I don't know anything about.

00:56:20.100 --> 00:56:24.460
[Guest 2]: And it's going to make me sound like I'm trying to make myself look good.

00:56:24.460 --> 00:56:30.220
[Guest 2]: But I think there's not enough of that, that we want our opinions confirmed more than challenged,

00:56:30.220 --> 00:56:34.680
[Guest 2]: that we want to be made to feel good rather than to learn more.

00:56:34.680 --> 00:56:36.900
[Guest 2]: And all of that kind of feeds into one another.

00:56:36.900 --> 00:56:43.940
[Guest 2]: And it's sad that as you know, as that was also just saying a little while ago, it's

00:56:43.940 --> 00:56:48.700
[Guest 2]: why are people pissed off with the mainstream media, we need to do a lot of introspection

00:56:48.700 --> 00:56:49.700
[Guest 2]: on that as well.

00:56:49.700 --> 00:56:55.840
[Guest 2]: There are lots of things I think that we in the big media have not got right by any means.

00:56:55.840 --> 00:56:59.100
[Guest 2]: And that's why people were so ready to believe the worst of us.

00:56:59.100 --> 00:57:02.460
[Guest 2]: And if we don't figure those out and find ways to deal with that, and if we don't figure

00:57:02.460 --> 00:57:09.180
[Guest 2]: out how to make it commercially viable to produce good journalism, we're screwed.

00:57:09.180 --> 00:57:10.180
[Guest 2]: I hope we will.

00:57:10.180 --> 00:57:14.900
[Guest 2]: I hope we will while I'm still earning a salary in the media, and you know, I've not found

00:57:14.900 --> 00:57:17.320
[Guest 2]: some other way to make an income.

00:57:17.320 --> 00:57:18.620
[Guest 1]: But it makes me worry.

00:57:18.620 --> 00:57:19.620
[Guest 1]: So,

00:57:19.620 --> 00:57:25.700
[Guest 1]: So despair, I thought I was, you know, spooning out the despair.

00:57:25.700 --> 00:57:33.620
[Guest 1]: My despair is, apart from all the things I mentioned is that a lot of fantastic youngsters

00:57:33.620 --> 00:57:38.060
[Guest 1]: who are coming to this profession, full of passion, full of ideas, full of willingness

00:57:38.060 --> 00:57:46.860
[Guest 1]: to do work, and journalism schools are full as you know, but are either not willing or

00:57:46.860 --> 00:57:54.460
[Guest 1]: not encouraged to do walk the streets and get the story.

00:57:54.460 --> 00:58:01.020
[Guest 1]: You know, Google, mobile phone, Wikipedia, one court formula, and there it goes.

00:58:01.020 --> 00:58:05.820
[Guest 1]: And you need bosses who say sorry, not working.

00:58:05.820 --> 00:58:19.180
[Guest 1]: So when I meet a I, we've just taken a guy who will go to extraordinarily remote places

00:58:19.180 --> 00:58:25.580
[Guest 1]: and come back with stories on not the usual rural distress and all that.

00:58:25.580 --> 00:58:27.460
[Guest 1]: But and not even rural hope.

00:58:27.460 --> 00:58:28.460
[Guest 1]: That's the other thing.

00:58:28.460 --> 00:58:30.780
[Guest 1]: Everything should not be hope or distress.

00:58:30.780 --> 00:58:36.980
[Guest 1]: But come back with state of the ground, a state of the grassroots stories, you know,

00:58:36.980 --> 00:58:39.780
[Guest 1]: bread and butter like work.

00:58:39.780 --> 00:58:45.860
[Guest 1]: And I if any young reporters listening to me, I would say to her, please go out and

00:58:45.860 --> 00:58:46.860
[Guest 1]: report.

00:58:46.860 --> 00:58:51.340
[Guest 1]: If you were talking about how you travel down the coast of Tamil Nadu, you were doing old

00:58:51.340 --> 00:58:57.020
[Guest 1]: fashioned solid ground reporting, you could have easily, you know, sat there and kind

00:58:57.020 --> 00:58:59.700
[Guest 1]: of assembled this that and the other.

00:58:59.700 --> 00:59:07.020
[Guest 1]: So I that's a professional despair that really, the hope is equally kind of it's actually

00:59:07.020 --> 00:59:08.020
[Guest 1]: connected.

00:59:08.020 --> 00:59:11.260
[Guest 1]: I get invited to speak to students everywhere.

00:59:11.260 --> 00:59:20.340
[Guest 1]: I'm in Pune day after tomorrow, speaking to you at a university, large numbers turn up.

00:59:20.340 --> 00:59:25.980
[Guest 1]: I like to think that we must be doing something which wants them to connect and listen to

00:59:25.980 --> 00:59:29.420
[Guest 1]: us, not because we are evangelists.

00:59:29.420 --> 00:59:33.100
[Guest 1]: I'm a corporate evangelist because I'm constantly looking for money.

00:59:33.100 --> 00:59:37.500
[Guest 1]: But we are not media evangelists at all.

00:59:37.500 --> 00:59:40.460
[Guest 1]: But that gives me hope.

00:59:40.460 --> 00:59:45.020
[Guest 1]: Public union elections in JNU have given me hope.

00:59:45.020 --> 00:59:50.100
[Guest 1]: Not because the leftists won, because they saw something about uniting that these opposition

00:59:50.100 --> 00:59:52.500
[Guest 1]: parties have not been able to understand.

00:59:52.500 --> 00:59:55.340
[Guest 1]: So all those things give me hope.

00:59:55.340 --> 00:59:58.540
[Guest 1]: You know, people say, oh, the emergency all over again, rubbish.

00:59:58.540 --> 01:00:00.860
[Guest 1]: The emergency was terrible.

01:00:00.860 --> 01:00:03.580
[Guest 1]: Things are not good, but it was terrible.

01:00:03.580 --> 01:00:10.900
[Guest 1]: But what really pisses me off and despairs is that the establishment, media establishment

01:00:10.900 --> 01:00:15.460
[Guest 1]: is letting down the side and its own staff and its own readers.

01:00:15.460 --> 01:00:22.980
[Guest 1]: So this I would end on when I see all these small efforts popping up and when you said

01:00:22.980 --> 01:00:27.060
[Guest 1]: somebody is making money on subscriptions and all that they are not successful in a

01:00:27.060 --> 01:00:28.060
[Guest 1]: huge way.

01:00:28.060 --> 01:00:36.180
[Guest 1]: The Times of India is 180 years old, but by something in a few years, you are going to

01:00:36.180 --> 01:00:40.780
[Guest 1]: see more and more youngsters coming in saying, hey, this is not working.

01:00:40.780 --> 01:00:45.980
[Guest 1]: I wanted to start something of my own or join somewhere, learn and then go out and do something

01:00:45.980 --> 01:00:46.980
[Guest 1]: on my own.

01:00:46.980 --> 01:00:53.260
[Guest 1]: So on the whole, I think I've been listening to you intently, Peter.

01:00:53.260 --> 01:00:58.380
[Guest 1]: Technology is going to be a huge driver of ideas and innovation.

01:00:58.380 --> 01:01:02.660
[Guest 1]: And if those old and new worlds can be married effectively, I think we are on to a damn good

01:01:02.660 --> 01:01:03.660
[Amit Varma]: track.

01:01:03.660 --> 01:01:05.700
[Amit Varma]: That's a great note of hope to end on.

01:01:05.700 --> 01:01:08.860
[Amit Varma]: More power to all the young people listening to the show want to make a change and more

01:01:08.860 --> 01:01:12.420
[Amit Varma]: power also to my fellow old fogies here, Peter and Siddharth.

01:01:12.420 --> 01:01:13.420
[Amit Varma]: Thank you so much for coming on the show.

